body:
## Steps to Reproduce
* Upload a dart package to a private github/gitlab repo
* Set up SSH based authentication
* Add the dependency as:
```
  my_package:
    git: git@gitlab.com:company/my_package.git
```
### When run in terminal as `flutter packages get`, 
It runs fine. When accessing hosted repository, it will ask for passphrase for the private SSH key

### When run using the Packages get button on top left of editor
![screenshot from 2019-01-09 15-19-05](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15698263/50891278-ef227580-1421-11e9-8c6b-190c53a564d9.png)

```
/home/raveesh/MyCode/sdk/flutter/bin/flutter --no-color packages get
Running "flutter packages get" in guru_app...      
```
comes up in the messages tab, and the plugin has no way to ask for a SSH password if prompted.
This is where the flutter command hangs and all flutter commands fails because `packages get` does not release the lock

### Current Solution
run:
```
sudo killall dart
```
and then run flutter packages get manually in terminal.

comment_data.body:
It's possible Dart should do better here.  But this also sounds like a common problem with `ssh` for which (as I understand it) `ssh-agent` exists to solve?

@zoechi I suspect this belongs in the pub repository and it's possible that pub should be calling git with different flags or environment to force it to error out instead of attempting to talk to an input stream which is not there.  For example, pub may need to set stdin to null or /dev/null when calling git to make it do the right thing.
I also think this should be reported in https://github.com/dart-lang/pub/issues
Not setting a password for SSH key also works :rofl:
@eseidelGoogle in case you wanted me to move the issue, I can't do that, only between repos where I'm member, and I'm not a member of `dart-lang/...` repos.
I will open a new issue in that case.

I note on https://github.com/dart-lang/pub/issues/2026 that `pub` forwards the system `SSH_AGENT`.
Probably the editor plugin needs to ensure that:
 * `pub` is not invoked in an interactive shell that users can't interact with, or that,
 * `DISPLAY` and `SSH_ASKPASS` is set if calling in an non-interactive shell.

See: https://man.openbsd.org/ssh#SSH_ASKPASS

But I'll admit there is a lot of subtle issues here, and getting this to work across platforms is not easy.

Steve this seems like an enhancement/feature.  However, I'm not sure of the work involved in the plugin seems like it could be a bit tricky.  I've marked as an enhancement for now but feel free to disagree.

@satyaattili 
1.  Are you using SSH agent?
2.  If you have SSH agent set up correctly a git clone from the repository in question should happen w/o any password prompt.
3.  If the git clone works, but the flutter pub packages get doesn't, try using `pub` directly.

If pub works, but `flutter`'s wrapper around pub `flutter packages get` doesn't, then this bug seems valid.  I would expect ssh-agent to "just work", it's designed to make ssh password prompts go away for tools like this.

I can't easily test from this computer myself, but do let us know the results of your tests, thanks!

I am facing this issue as well. On windows, adding a key to the agent via `ssh-add` doesn't even have an effect on subsequent `pub get` calls in the same terminal for some reason. Key just gets ignored and the pub get fails.

https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/issues/3055#issuecomment-472016543

This would resolve it for the time being. Using ssh-agent for this is the right way to move forward. We need to configure the ASK_PASS and DISPLAY environment variables for the same.

Final suggestions from personal experience,
1. Use passwordless SSH keys to avoid the problem entirely
2. If using SSH keys with passwords, configure DISPLAY and ASK_PASS for ssh environment properly

@jonasfj  link to a guide/tutorial on how to configure ssh-agent would be really helpful. I tried looking for resources but not much is available here. For myself, I just want to know which file to add these environment variables (Linux / Ubuntu).

also, what's with ssh-add? Does it require passwords to be input just once? It could also be a possible solution.

Stumbled upon this and it fixed my problem on windows 10 command line:

https://github.com/desktop/desktop/issues/5641#issuecomment-421801704
